 retaining a sensitivity to regional distinctiveness.Drawing on the approaches of social history, this study moves beyond the history of the strike and union organization that characterizes conventional labour history, and re-examines what was once called the 'western revolt.' The Workers' Revolt in Canada combines fresh archival research with a great body of secondary literature on the subject to produce a compelling new synthesis, which will be of great use to teachers and of interest to economists, sociologists, and historians.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aLabor movementzCanadaxHistoryy20th century. 0aWorking classzCanadaxHistoryy20th century. 7aHISTORY / Canada / General.2bisacsh1 aEwen, Geoffrey, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHeron, Craig, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHeron, Craig, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMckay, Ian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMitchell, Tom, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMorton, Suzanne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNaylor, James, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRoth, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSeager, Allen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSiemiatycki, Myer, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press eBook-Package Archive 1933-1999z978311049094740uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978144268256640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781442682566423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781442682566.jpg  a978-3-11-049094-7  University of 